  "style": "APA",
  "texts": [
    "While imitation typically suggests deception rather than the accurate production of knowledge, it serves as the foundation for various forms of cultural learning (Tennie et al. 2009), and therefore is not inherently negative.",
    "Thus, the crucial factor lies in evaluating the quality of imitation, distinguishing between performances that enhance knowledge and those that perpetuate ignorance.",
    "This evaluation becomes particularly significant for semantic technologies capable of generating natural language in a highly imitative manner, according to specific parameters.",
    "Consequently, the issue outlined here raises two fundamental questions: first, the notion of imitation in artificial systems, starting from how it was conceptualized by Turing; and second, the evaluation of artificial systems themselves for their performance and results, a topic that has gained relevance in the ongoing AI debate.",
    "The article will delve into the dual issue of examining the impact of LLMs and related semantic technologies on the dissemination and production of texts, especially via the Internet."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "While imitation typically suggests deception rather than the accurate production of knowledge, it serves as the foundation for various forms of cultural learning (Tennie et al. 2009), and therefore is not inherently negative."
  ]
}